What is the Yocto Project?

The Yocto Project is an open source collaboration project that helps developers create custom Linux-based systems that are designed for embedded products regardless of the product’s hardware architecture. Yocto Project provides a flexible toolset and a development environment that allows embedded device developers across the world to collaborate through shared technologies, software stacks, configurations, and best practices used to create these tailored Linux images.

Some Basic Terms

Recipe
A recipe is a set of instructions that defines how a particular software component is fetched, configured, compiled, installed, and packaged by BitBake. 

BitBake:
BitBake is a task-based build engine used by the Yocto Project to parse recipes, resolve dependencies, and execute tasks to build software packages and complete Linux images for embedded systems.

Metadata:
Metadata is the complete set of structured information—written as variables, configuration, and task definitions—that describes how software components are sourced, configured, built, installed, packaged, and assembled into a final system, and is interpreted and executed by BitBake to produce a customized Linux image.

Meta layer:
A meta layer (or simply layer) in the Yocto Project is a logical collection of metadata—such as recipes (.bb), append files (.bbappend), configuration files, and classes—that groups related functionality and defines how specific software, features, or hardware support are integrated into the build system, which is then processed by BitBake to generate the final system.

BSP:
BSP (Board Support Package) in the Yocto Project is a collection of hardware-specific metadata, configurations, and components that define how the build system should support and generate a Linux system for a particular target board, including its kernel, bootloader, device tree, and low-level settings, which are processed by BitBake.

.bb (Recipe File)
A .bb file (BitBake recipe) is a metadata file that defines the complete instructions to fetch, configure, compile, install, and package a specific software component, which is parsed and executed by BitBake within the Yocto Project.

.bbappend (Recipe Append File)
A .bbappend file is a metadata file used to extend or modify an existing .bb recipe without altering the original recipe, allowing additional configurations, patches, or changes to be layered on top in a modular and maintainable way within the Yocto build system.

Poky:
Poky is the reference distribution of the Yocto Project that provides a complete, ready-to-use build environment, including the BitBake build engine, core metadata, and default configuration layers required to build custom embedded Linux images.

Package
A package in the Yocto Project is a binary output generated from a recipe that contains compiled files, libraries, and associated metadata, which can be installed into the target root filesystem or used by BitBake to assemble the final Linux image.


Development HOST:
A development host or Build Host is key to using the Yocto Project. Because the goal of the Yocto Project is to develop images or applications that run on embedded hardware, development of those images and applications generally takes place on a system not intended to run the software — the development host.

1.Use a Supported Linux Distribution: You should have a reasonably current Linux-based host system. You will have the best results with a recent release of Fedora, openSUSE, Debian, Ubuntu, RHEL or CentOS as these releases are frequently tested against the Yocto Project and officially supported
2.Minimum Free Disk Space:To build an image such as core-image-sato for the qemux86-64 machine, you need a system with at least 90 Gbytes of free disk space. However, much more disk space will be necessary to build more complex images, to run multiple builds and to cache build artifacts, improving build efficiency.
Minimum System RAM:You will manage to build an image such as core-image-sato for the qemux86-64 machine with as little as 8 Gbytes of RAM on an old system with 4 CPU cores, but your builds will be much faster on a system with as much RAM and as many CPU cores as possible.

3.Install Development Host Packages: Required development host packages vary depending on your build host and what you want to do with the Yocto Project.
$ sudo apt install build-essential chrpath cpio debianutils diffstat file gawk gcc git iputils-ping libacl1 liblz4-tool locales python3 python3-git python3-jinja2 python3-pexpect python3-pip python3-subunit socat texinfo unzip wget xz-utils zstd
4.ou also need to ensure you have the en_US.UTF-8 locale enabled:

$ locale --all-locales | grep en_US.utf8

If this is not the case, you can reconfigure the locales package to add it (requires an interactive shell):

$ sudo dpkg-reconfigure locales


Getting started to build first image:


Step 1: Prepare Host System
✅ What you do

Install required packages on Ubuntu.

🧠 What happens internally

Yocto depends on many host tools:

gcc, make → native compilation tools
git, wget → fetch source code
python3 → BitBake execution
chrpath, cpio, xz → packaging & filesystem creation

👉 These tools allow BitBake to run properly.

Step 2: Download Yocto (Poky)
git clone git://git.yoctoproject.org/poky
cd poky
git checkout kirkstone
🧠 What is happening
You download Poky
Poky contains:
BitBake
Core metadata (meta, meta-poky, meta-yocto-bsp)
Default configs

👉 This is your base build system

Step 3: Initialize Build Environment
source oe-init-build-env
🧠 Internally this does:
Sets environment variables:
BBPATH
PATH (adds BitBake tools)
Creates build directory:
build/
 ├── conf/
 │   ├── local.conf
 │   └── bblayers.conf
Moves you into build/

👉 This step prepares everything for building.

Step 4: Add Raspberry Pi BSP Layer
cd ..
git clone https://git.yoctoproject.org/meta-raspberrypi
🧠 Internally
You add meta-raspberrypi
This layer provides:
Kernel config for Pi
Bootloader setup
Device tree
GPU/firmware settings

👉 Without this → Yocto cannot build for Raspberry Pi
Step 5: Add Layer to Build System

Edit:

build/conf/bblayers.conf

Add:

../meta-raspberrypi
🧠 Internally
BitBake reads bblayers.conf
Only listed layers are considered

👉 If not added:

Recipes in that layer are ignored

Step 6: Configure Target Machine

Edit:

build/conf/local.conf

Set:

MACHINE = "raspberrypi4"
🧠 Internally
Yocto selects:
Kernel config
Bootloader
Architecture (ARM64)
Device-specific settings

👉 This connects your build to actual hardware.

Step 7: Additional Configuration
ENABLE_UART = "1"
IMAGE_FSTYPES += "rpi-sdimg"
🧠 What these do
ENABLE_UART → enables serial console
IMAGE_FSTYPES → tells Yocto to generate SD card image

👉 Controls final output behavior

Step 8: Start Build
bitbake core-image-minimal

👉 Using BitBake


Step 9: What Happens During Build (Very Important)
9.1 Metadata Parsing

BitBake reads:

All recipes
Config files
Classes

👉 Builds internal database

9.2 Dependency Resolution

BitBake determines:

Required packages
Build order

Example:

Image
 → busybox
 → libc
 → kernel
9.3 Task Graph Creation

Creates DAG (Directed Acyclic Graph):

Each node:

do_fetch
do_compile
etc.
9.4 SSTATE Cache Check
If already built → reuse
Else → build from scratch
9.5 Task Execution Pipeline

For each recipe:

🔹 Fetch

Download source code
→ stored in:

downloads/
🔹 Unpack

Extract code
→ stored in:

tmp/work/
🔹 Configure

Runs:

./configure
or cmake
🔹 Compile
Cross-compilation happens
Host builds ARM binaries
🔹 Install

Files copied into staging area:

${D}/usr/bin/
${D}/etc/
🔹 Package

Creates:

.ipk / .deb / .rpm


Step 12: Output Storage

Location:

build/tmp/deploy/images/raspberrypi4/

Contains:

Image file
Kernel
Device tree


Flow Summary:
Install host tools
        ↓
Download Poky
        ↓
Setup build environment
        ↓
Add Raspberry Pi layer
        ↓
Configure MACHINE
        ↓
Run bitbake
        ↓
Fetch → Configure → Compile → Install
        ↓
Package creation
        ↓
Root filesystem
        ↓
Image generation
        ↓
Flash SD card
        ↓
Boot device


